{"id": "eff5a521d8db420e85ae4cc179cad338", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:57:31", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Selected Action: Action 1.  \nReasoning: We have now established a sufficiently robust and innovative conceptual foundation for our research direction, with clear technical differentiation and high practical relevance. The core idea—using adaptive temperature control in a contrastive self-training framework as a mechanism to balance confidence and generalization—is not only well-motivated by empirical shortcomings of existing methods (e.g., confirmation bias, poor calibration under imbalance), but we’ve also begun grounding it in principled frameworks such as information theory and meta-learning. This gives us both a strong heuristic *and* a pathway toward theoretical justification.\n\nMoreover, the proposed integration of representation quality (via contrastive uniformity/alignment) with pseudo-label calibration introduces a novel feedback loop that goes beyond standard co-training or fixed scheduling. Our refined research question is specific, falsifiable, and aligned with real-world challenges in medical and long-tailed vision tasks. We’ve identified concrete evaluation metrics (ECE, worst-class accuracy, robustness to shift), benchmarks (CIFAR-10-LT, ImageNet-LT, medical datasets), and potential mechanisms (bilevel optimization, control-theoretic adaptation).\n\nWhile deeper exploration into Bayesian uncertainty or causal signals could enrich the adaptation rule, these can be incorporated as extensions during ablation studies or follow-up work. Delaying topic selection further risks diminishing returns on discussion without proportional gains in clarity. By selecting the topic now, we enable forward progress on implementation, experimental design, and baseline comparisons—critical next steps that will themselves inform and refine the framework.\n\nTherefore, I believe we are ready to commit to this research direction while retaining flexibility to evolve the method iteratively based on empirical feedback.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "28fd7573383d4d02af186cafb61be322", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:57:31", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "[retrieved]:", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "3726ab43095d4adc95df1dce5c43c0f1", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:57:39", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Thought: The proposed research direction represents a significant and timely advancement in semi-supervised learning by addressing a core limitation—confirmation bias due to overconfident pseudo-labels—through an adaptive, theoretically informed mechanism. By reframing temperature not as a static hyperparameter but as a dynamic, feedback-driven variable linked to both contrastive representation quality and predictive uncertainty, the approach bridges gaps between empirical success and theoretical understanding. This integration of information-theoretic principles (e.g., effective margin control via softmax temperature) with meta-learning and control theory enables a principled adaptation strategy that responds to data distribution shifts and class imbalance. The focus on calibration (via ECE), robustness (worst-group accuracy), and generalization aligns with real-world deployment needs, particularly in high-stakes domains like medical imaging. Furthermore, the use of bilevel optimization or differentiable validation signals introduces a novel training paradigm where the model learns *how* to trust its own predictions adaptively. While extensions from Bayesian or causal learning could enhance it, the current formulation is sufficiently innovative, falsifiable, and implementable to serve as a strong foundational topic. Delaying further would hinder progress without proportional conceptual gain.\n\nTopic: ```json{\"Selected Topic\": \"Adaptive Temperature Control in Contrastive Self-Training: A Meta-Learning Framework for Balancing Confidence and Generalization in Imbalanced Semi-Supervised Learning\"}```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "a1152b8b04bb42289ece479c2f3b7e09", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:57:44", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "The selected research topic focuses on adaptive temperature control within a contrastive self-training framework, using meta-learning to dynamically balance model confidence and generalization in imbalanced semi-supervised learning. By treating temperature as a learnable, feedback-driven parameter—linked to representation quality and uncertainty—the approach addresses confirmation bias and poor calibration in pseudo-labeling. It integrates principles from information theory, meta-learning, and control theory, with evaluation centered on calibration (ECE), robustness (worst-class accuracy), and performance under distribution shifts. The method is designed for practical impact in domains like medical imaging and supports iterative refinement through ablation and extension. The team agrees it is sufficiently novel, testable, and implementable to move forward without further delay.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "83a7f3afdede4d92a03ef191c00c8234", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:58:20", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Thought: The core challenge in pseudo-label-based self-training lies in the tension between confidence and generalization. When models assign pseudo-labels to unlabeled data, overly confident but incorrect labels can propagate noise and degrade performance—a phenomenon exacerbated when temperature scaling is fixed and static. Inspired by Paper 1’s use of adaptive temperature for calibration, Paper 3’s differentiable teacher-student dynamics, and the broader need for dynamic control in learning systems, I propose a novel framework that learns an adaptive temperature policy conditioned on uncertainty, consistency, and feature-space density. Unlike ATS, which applies post-hoc calibration using token-level features, our method integrates adaptive temperature directly into contrastive self-training as a learnable, input-dependent policy that modulates both classification and representation learning. This goes beyond mere calibration: it actively shapes the student’s learning trajectory by balancing exploitation (high-confidence pseudo-labels) and exploration (uncertain regions where temperature is increased to soften predictions). Furthermore, unlike DRIFT’s game-theoretic formulation that focuses on weight differentiation, we introduce a meta-learned temperature controller that dynamically adjusts based on three principled signals: prediction entropy (uncertainty), agreement across augmentations (consistency), and local feature density (to detect out-of-distribution or sparse regions). By making temperature a function of these context-aware metrics rather than a global hyperparameter, the model becomes more robust to label noise and better at generalizing across diverse data distributions. The integration with contrastive learning adds another layer of benefit—while pseudo-labels guide categorical alignment, contrastive loss ensures semantic smoothness in the embedding space. Our approach thus unifies representation learning and label refinement under a single adaptive mechanism, enabling safer and more effective use of unlabeled data.\n\nNew Idea: ```json\n{\n  \"Idea\": \"We propose a novel contrastive self-training framework called LATE-CT (Learned Adaptive Temperature Control for Contrastive Training), which introduces a meta-learned temperature policy network that dynamically adjusts the softmax temperature during pseudo-label generation based on three key signals: (1) predictive uncertainty (measured via entropy over class probabilities), (2) inter-augmentation prediction consistency (via KL divergence between views), and (3) local feature-space density (estimated using k-nearest neighbor distances in the encoder embedding space). The temperature policy network is trained end-to-end alongside the main classifier and encoder using a bilevel optimization setup, where the lower-level objective improves classification accuracy and representation quality via joint contrastive and cross-entropy losses, while the upper-level objective optimizes for generalization by minimizing validation error on a small labeled proxy set. This allows the temperature to be lowered in high-density, low-uncertainty, consistent regions (favoring confident pseudo-labels) and raised in sparse, inconsistent, or uncertain regions (encouraging conservative, softened outputs). Crucially, the temperature is applied not only to the classification head but also modulates the distribution used in contrastive loss construction (e.g., in neighborhood sampling or positive pair weighting), creating a unified adaptive mechanism across both discriminative and representational objectives. This differs from prior work in several ways: unlike fixed or manually scheduled temperatures, our method learns a context-sensitive policy; unlike post-hoc calibration (e.g., ATS), it is tightly integrated into training dynamics; and unlike non-differentiable teacher-student updates, our framework enables gradient-based adaptation of the temperature controller through implicit differentiation. We evaluate LATE-CT on semi-supervised image classification benchmarks (CIFAR-10/100, STL-10, ImageNet-1K) under varying label ratios and domain shift conditions. We expect significant gains in both accuracy and calibration metrics (ECE, Brier score), particularly in low-label regimes where pseudo-label noise is most harmful. Additionally, ablation studies will isolate the contribution of each input signal (uncertainty, consistency, density) to policy effectiveness. The idea has strong potential to influence how confidence is managed in self-supervised and semi-supervised learning, offering a principled alternative to heuristic thresholding or fixed sharpening.\",\n  \"Title\": \"LATE-CT: Learned Adaptive Temperature Control for Contrastive Self-Training via Uncertainty, Consistency, and Feature-Space Density\",\n  \"Experiment\": \"The experimental design involves four main phases: (1) Architecture Design: Implement a dual-path network with a backbone encoder (e.g., ResNet-18/50), a classification head, and a lightweight MLP as the temperature policy network taking as input the concatenated features of uncertainty (entropy), consistency (KL divergence across augmented views), and feature density (kNN distance in embedding space). (2) Training Protocol: Use a standard semi-supervised split (e.g., 4k/10k labels for CIFAR-100). Train using stochastic bilevel optimization: inner loop updates encoder and classifier using supervised loss on labeled data and pseudo-labeled loss (with current temperature) on unlabeled data, combined with InfoNCE-style contrastive loss; outer loop updates the temperature policy using validation loss on a held-out labeled subset. Pseudo-labels are generated with temperature-scaled softmax, and gradients are passed through using straight-through estimators if necessary. (3) Baselines & Comparisons: Compare against FixMatch, SimCLR, UPS, and ATS-integrated variants. Evaluate under varying data scarcity and corruption (e.g., noisy augmentations). (4) Evaluation Metrics: Report top-1 accuracy, ECE, Brier score, and label usage efficiency (accuracy per labeled sample). Ideal outcomes include >3% improvement over FixMatch at 10% labeling, reduced overconfidence in low-density regions, and smoother decision boundaries in t-SNE visualizations.\",\n  \"Clarity\": 9,\n  \"Feasibility\": 8,\n  \"Novelty\": 9\n}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[96mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "50c3827c6d1c43db8d64671f9695627a", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:59:09", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Thought: The original LATE-CT idea presents a compelling integration of adaptive temperature control into contrastive self-training, leveraging uncertainty, consistency, and feature-space density. However, it relies on a bilevel optimization framework that may be computationally expensive and sensitive to hyperparameters, especially in low-label regimes where the validation proxy set is small. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1 (ATS), which uses post-hoc calibration with input-dependent temperature prediction, and Paper 3, which introduces lightweight yet effective contrastive tuning mechanisms, I propose a shift from end-to-end bilevel learning to a more stable, modular, and scalable approach. My key insight is to decouple the *learning* of the temperature policy from the main training loop by introducing a **meta-calibration network** trained offline on a diverse set of model trajectories, enabling generalization across datasets and label ratios. This meta-network learns to map local representation geometry, predictive dynamics, and consistency signals directly to optimal temperature values that balance pseudo-label confidence and robustness. Crucially, unlike ATS—which applies temperature after training—our method integrates this learned policy *during* training as a plug-in adaptive module, preserving gradients via differentiable approximation. Furthermore, inspired by Paper 2’s emphasis on balanced adaptation under distributional shifts, I incorporate **class-aware density estimation** in the embedding space to prevent overconfidence in minority-class regions, addressing a critical flaw in current pseudo-labeling methods under class imbalance. The resulting framework, MetaTemp-CT, unifies meta-learning, contrastive learning, and self-training with a focus on adaptive calibration grounded in both local semantics and global data structure. It differs from prior work by being dataset-agnostic in its temperature policy design, avoiding costly online meta-updates, while still enabling dynamic, context-sensitive temperature modulation throughout training.\n\nNew Idea: ```json{\n  \"Idea\": \"We propose MetaTemp-CT (Meta-Learned Temperature Control for Contrastive Self-Training), a novel framework that leverages a pre-trained meta-calibration network to dynamically adjust the softmax temperature during pseudo-label generation in semi-supervised learning. Unlike existing approaches that either use fixed temperatures or learn them through complex online bilevel optimization (e.g., LATE-CT), MetaTemp-CT employs a lightweight, generalizable meta-network trained offline on a broad corpus of training trajectories across multiple datasets (CIFAR-10/100, STL-10, TinyImageNet), label ratios (1%–50%), and corruption levels. This meta-network takes as input three real-time signals extracted from the student model: (1) predictive uncertainty (entropy over class probabilities), (2) inter-augmentation consistency (symmetric KL divergence between two augmented views), and (3) class-conditional feature-space density (computed via kNN distances within predicted class clusters in the encoder space). To address class imbalance and avoid overconfident labeling in underrepresented regions, we introduce a normalized density score that adjusts for relative class frequency in the neighborhood. The output of the meta-network is a scalar temperature value applied to the softmax operator used in pseudo-label generation and also modulates the sampling distribution in the contrastive loss (e.g., reweighting positive pairs based on alignment confidence). The meta-network itself is trained using a meta-objective that minimizes the discrepancy between predicted temperatures and oracle temperatures derived from ablation studies—specifically, those temperatures that maximize validation accuracy while minimizing expected calibration error (ECE) over rolling windows in training. Once trained, the meta-network acts as a plug-in module that requires no fine-tuning and can be deployed across new tasks with minimal adaptation. This design enables fast, stable, and interpretable temperature control without the computational overhead of implicit differentiation or second-order gradients. We further enhance robustness by incorporating a gating mechanism that disables temperature updates when prediction entropy exceeds a threshold, preventing harmful propagation of noisy labels. MetaTemp-CT bridges the gap between post-hoc calibration (like ATS) and online self-training dynamics, offering a best-of-both-worlds solution: adaptivity without instability. We evaluate MetaTemp-CT on standard benchmarks under extreme label scarcity (e.g., 1k labels on CIFAR-100) and domain-shift conditions (e.g., CIFAR-C). We expect significant improvements in top-1 accuracy (>4% over FixMatch), reduced ECE (by ~60%), and better label efficiency, particularly in imbalanced settings. Ablation studies will assess the contribution of each input signal and the impact of class-aware density normalization.\",\n  \"Title\": \"MetaTemp-CT: Meta-Learned Adaptive Temperature Control for Robust Contrastive Self-Training via Uncertainty, Consistency, and Class-Aware Density\",\n  \"Experiment\": \"The experimental plan consists of four stages: (1) Meta-Network Pre-Training: Collect training trajectories from multiple models (ResNet, WRN) trained under various label ratios and augmentations across five datasets. For each step, record the three input signals and compute the 'oracle' temperature that would have minimized downstream validation error over the next epoch. Train the meta-network (a 3-layer MLP) via regression to predict this oracle temperature. (2) Integration with Self-Training: Implement MetaTemp-CT within a FixMatch-style pipeline with SimCLR-based contrastive loss. At each iteration, extract the three signals from the current mini-batch, feed them into the frozen meta-network, obtain the temperature, and apply it to both pseudo-label sharpening and contrastive neighbor weighting. (3) Evaluation Protocol: Benchmark on CIFAR-10/100, STL-10, and ImageNet-1K with 1%, 5%, 10%, and 25% labeled data. Include corrupted variants (CIFAR-C) to test robustness. Compare against FixMatch, UPS, ReMixMatch, ATS-integrated baselines, and LATE-CT. Use ResNet-50 and ViT-B/16 backbones. (4) Metrics & Analysis: Report top-1 accuracy, ECE, Brier score, and decision boundary smoothness via t-SNE with confidence coloring. Conduct ablations on individual input features, class-aware density, and gating mechanism. Ideal outcomes include consistent gains across datasets, improved calibration in tail classes, and faster convergence due to stabilized pseudo-labeling.\",\n  \"Clarity\": 9,\n  \"Feasibility\": 8,\n  \"Novelty\": 9\n}```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[96mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "d82fede138d0492ea068d9d5993299d6", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 01:59:40", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Thought: My motivation stems from the persistent challenge in semi-supervised learning (SSL) of effectively leveraging unlabeled data without amplifying confirmation bias or overfitting to incorrect pseudo-labels—especially under class imbalance. While contrastive self-training (CST) has shown promise by combining representation learning with pseudo-labeling, it often struggles to balance confidence and generalization due to static temperature scaling in the softmax distribution used for pseudo-label generation. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s use of self-training for counterfactual imputation and Paper 2’s integration of contrastive signals into dynamic model components (e.g., attention), I propose embedding meta-learning into the temperature adaptation mechanism. This would allow the model to *learn how to adjust temperature dynamically* based on uncertainty, class frequency, and representation consistency across epochs—particularly crucial in imbalanced settings where rare classes are easily overwhelmed by high-confidence dominant ones. Unlike heuristic temperature schedules, a meta-learned controller can adaptively modulate the sharpness of prediction distributions to promote both exploration (via softer distributions early on) and exploitation (via sharper ones later), while preventing premature convergence to biased pseudo-labels. Furthermore, integrating a contrastive loss that operates on both labeled and confidently pseudo-labeled samples ensures that decision boundaries are informed not just by label predictions but also by semantic similarity—a synergy underexplored in current adaptive SSL frameworks. The novelty lies in unifying meta-learning with temperature control within a contrastive self-training loop, creating a feedback system where the learning dynamics themselves are optimized for long-term generalization rather than short-term accuracy gains.\n\nNew Idea: ```json\n{\n  \"Idea\": \"We propose a novel framework titled 'Adaptive Temperature Control in Contrastive Self-Training: A Meta-Learning Framework for Balancing Confidence and Generalization in Imbalanced Semi-Supervised Learning'. This work introduces a meta-learning module that dynamically controls the temperature parameter in the softmax layer during pseudo-label generation, conditioned on real-time metrics such as per-class prediction entropy, label distribution skew, and inter-sample feature contrastiveness. Traditional CST methods apply fixed or manually scheduled temperatures, which fail to account for evolving model confidence and data imbalances during training. Our approach learns an adaptive policy—via a lightweight LSTM-based meta-controller—that observes these statistics across training epochs and outputs optimal temperature values per class or globally. The controller is trained using a meta-objective that maximizes validation performance on a small held-out labeled set, ensuring that temperature adjustments lead to improved generalization. Concurrently, we enhance the contrastive loss by selectively sampling anchor-positive pairs from both ground-truth labeled data and high-confidence pseudo-labeled examples, while excluding low-confidence or ambiguous instances to prevent noise propagation. Crucially, the temperature directly influences which pseudo-labels qualify as 'high-confidence', forming a closed-loop system where better calibration leads to cleaner contrastive learning, which in turn improves downstream classification. We evaluate this method on imbalanced semi-supervised benchmarks (e.g., CIFAR-10-LT, CIFAR-100-LT, and STL-10) with varying label ratios and imbalance factors. We expect significant improvements over state-of-the-art methods like FixMatch, UniMatch, and AdaMixer, particularly in low-data and high-imbalance regimes. The framework also provides interpretability through the learned temperature trajectories, revealing how different classes evolve in terms of required regularization over time. This work bridges meta-learning, contrastive representation learning, and robust pseudo-labeling, offering a principled solution to one of SSL's core dilemmas: when to trust the model’s own predictions.\",\n  \"Title\": \"Meta-Temperature: Meta-Learned Adaptive Temperature Control for Robust Contrastive Self-Training in Imbalanced Semi-Supervised Learning\",\n  \"Experiment\": \"The experimental design involves three phases: (1) Baseline setup using ResNet-50 or WRN-28-2 backbones on imbalanced variants of standard vision datasets (CIFAR-10/100-LT with 100–1000 labeled samples and imbalance ratio 10–100). Data augmentation follows RandAugment and CTAugment. (2) Implementation of the main framework: a dual-path architecture where the primary model generates features and pseudo-labels, while the meta-controller (a small LSTM) takes as input per-epoch statistics—mean entropy, class-wise confidence variance, and feature space compactness measured via intra-class similarity—and outputs a temperature scalar (or vector for class-specific control). The controller is updated via REINFORCE or implicit differentiation using a small validation set. (3) Integration of asymmetric contrastive loss that treats strongly augmented views of confident pseudo-labeled samples as positives only if their temperature-scaled probability exceeds a threshold. Ablation studies will test: fixed vs. scheduled vs. meta-learned temperature; presence/absence of contrastive loss; and uniform vs. meta-adaptive sampling. Evaluation metrics include overall accuracy, per-class accuracy (especially for rare classes), F1-score, and calibration error. Ideal outcomes include >5% improvement in mean per-class accuracy over FixMatch under extreme imbalance and demonstration of stable, interpretable temperature decay patterns correlated with learning progress.\",\n  \"Clarity\": 9,\n  \"Feasibility\": 8,\n  \"Novelty\": 9\n}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "ce7499049eb74195a34d6fa0274ebc00", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 02:00:24", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "Thought: The original idea of using a meta-learned controller for adaptive temperature in contrastive self-training is strong, but it relies on an auxiliary LSTM module that observes scalar statistics and outputs temperatures via reinforcement or implicit gradients. While effective, this design treats the meta-controller as a separate, opaque component and may struggle with generalization across diverse data distributions or architectures. Inspired by Papers 1 and 2, which demonstrate that language models can internalize task adaptation through in-context learning and instruction-based meta-tuning, I propose shifting from an external meta-controller to an *internalized, context-aware adaptive mechanism* that leverages the model’s own learned representations to regulate temperature. This eliminates the need for a separate controller and instead embeds adaptivity directly into the network’s inference process. Furthermore, drawing from Paper 3’s insight about decoupling components for robust task inference under uncertainty, I propose to decouple confidence calibration (temperature) from representation learning in the contrastive space—ensuring that temperature adaptation does not distort feature geometry. My key innovation is a **self-conditioned temperature modulation mechanism**, where the model generates its own context vectors from recent prediction dynamics (e.g., entropy trends, agreement between augmentations, class frequency estimates), and uses them to modulate the softmax temperature via a lightweight gating network *within* the model. This creates a closed-loop, self-adaptive system that is more scalable, interpretable, and architecture-agnostic than prior approaches. Unlike existing methods that use fixed or externally controlled temperatures, this framework enables each sample or class to dynamically adjust its calibration based on local evidence, improving both confidence reliability and generalization—especially critical in imbalanced semi-supervised settings where rare classes are easily overwhelmed.\n\nNew Idea: ```json{\n  \"Idea\": \"We propose a novel paradigm titled 'Self-Conditioned Adaptive Temperature Modulation (SCATM)' for contrastive self-training, which eliminates the need for external meta-controllers by embedding adaptive temperature learning directly within the model's inference pipeline. Instead of relying on a separate LSTM-based meta-learner to suggest temperature values based on epoch-level statistics, SCATM equips the primary model with a lightweight context aggregation and gating module that operates at the batch level. This module collects real-time signals such as per-class prediction entropy, inter-augmentation consistency, pseudo-label stability over recent epochs, and estimated label distribution skew. These signals are encoded into a compact context vector, which is then used to generate class-specific or sample-wise temperature scalars via a small learnable gating network (e.g., a single-layer MLP with sigmoid activation). Crucially, the gating network is trained end-to-end alongside the main model using a validation-aware meta-objective: during training, a small held-out labeled set is used to compute a differentiable proxy of generalization performance (e.g., cross-entropy loss), which guides the backpropagation of gradients through the temperature pathway. To prevent interference between representation learning and calibration, we decouple the contrastive and classification objectives following a dual-head architecture—one head handles supervised and pseudo-labeled classification with adaptive temperature scaling, while the other performs contrastive learning using only high-confidence samples selected via the same temperature-gated confidence measure. This ensures that noisy pseudo-labels do not corrupt the feature space. Moreover, SCATM introduces a memory buffer to track historical prediction patterns per class, enabling long-term adaptation especially for rare classes that appear infrequently. By internalizing the meta-learning signal, SCATM achieves faster convergence, better transfer across datasets, and improved robustness to imbalance without increasing architectural complexity. We expect this method to outperform both fixed-temperature and externally controlled baselines, particularly in low-label regimes (<100 labeled examples) and extreme imbalance (ratio >100), while offering greater transparency through interpretable context-to-temperature mappings.\",\n  \"Title\": \"SCATM: Self-Conditioned Adaptive Temperature Modulation for Robust Contrastive Self-Training in Imbalanced Semi-Supervised Learning\",\n  \"Experiment\": \"The experimental framework will be implemented in three stages. First, we establish baselines on imbalanced semi-supervised benchmarks including CIFAR-10-LT, CIFAR-100-LT, and ImageNet-LT, using standard backbones (ResNet-50, WRN-28-2) and label ratios (1%, 5%, 10%). Data augmentation follows FixMatch-style pipelines with RandAugment and CTAugment. Second, we implement the SCATM framework: (1) the context encoder aggregates per-batch statistics—mean entropy, prediction variance, consistency loss, and moving average of class frequencies—into a 64-dim context vector; (2) a gating network maps this vector to a K-dimensional temperature vector (K = number of classes) with values constrained to [0.1, 2.0] via softplus; (3) the classification head applies temperature-scaled softmax for pseudo-label generation and cross-entropy loss; (4) a separate projection head computes asymmetric contrastive loss using positive pairs from strongly augmented views of samples with confidence > threshold (determined by temperature-scaled output). The gating network is updated using implicit differentiation through a validation loss computed on a small labeled holdout set (~10% of labeled data). Third, ablation studies will evaluate: (a) context components (with/without memory buffer), (b) global vs. class-specific temperature, (c) end-to-end vs. detached gating updates, and (d) comparison against Meta-Temperature, AdaMatch, and UniMatch. Evaluation metrics include overall accuracy, mean per-class accuracy, F1-score, ECE (expected calibration error), and temperature trajectory analysis. Ideal outcomes include >6% improvement in per-class accuracy on CIFAR-100-LT under 1% labeling and demonstration of stable, interpretable temperature adaptation—e.g., higher initial temperatures for rare classes that gradually decrease as confidence grows.\",\n  \"Clarity\": 9,\n  \"Feasibility\": 8,\n  \"Novelty\": 10\n}```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "81fa9965dd1547968242fd7e14921c21", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 02:00:46", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "THOUGHT:  \nBoth Idea 0 (LATE-CT) and Idea 1 (MetaTemp-CT) propose highly novel frameworks for adaptive temperature control in contrastive self-training, leveraging uncertainty, consistency, and feature-space density to improve pseudo-labeling. However, when evaluating against existing literature, the distinction lies in their learning paradigms and novelty relative to prior work.\n\nIdea 0 introduces a **bilevel optimization framework** with an end-to-end learned temperature policy network that is updated via implicit differentiation through validation loss. While bilevel optimization is known in meta-learning (e.g., MAML, DaMSTF), its application to *temperature control in contrastive self-training*—especially with joint modulation of both classification and contrastive losses—is not directly covered in the provided papers. Paper 4 (CTKD) proposes a learnable curriculum temperature for knowledge distillation but uses a fixed schedule rather than context-dependent, input-driven adaptation. Paper 3 (ATS) is post-hoc and non-differentiable, whereas LATE-CT integrates temperature learning into training dynamics, which is more principled and tightly coupled. The use of implicit gradients to train a controller over temperature—a hyperparameter typically hand-tuned or scheduled—is a strong technical contribution. Moreover, applying temperature not only to pseudo-labels but also to contrastive pair weighting adds architectural novelty.\n\nIdea 1, MetaTemp-CT, proposes a **pre-trained, generalizable meta-network** trained offline on diverse trajectories to predict \"oracle\" temperatures. This resembles meta-learning setups such as those in Paper 5 (DaMSTF), which also uses meta-learning to weight instances in self-training, and Paper 1 (MetaCARD), which uses task uncertainty feedback. More critically, the concept of training a meta-model to predict optimal hyperparameters (like temperature) from training dynamics echoes ideas in hyperparameter optimization and meta-regression, which are increasingly explored. While the class-aware density normalization and gating mechanism add value, the core idea of using a pre-trained network to guide temperature selection based on signals like entropy and consistency overlaps more significantly with existing trends in meta-calibration and offline meta-control (as seen in ATS-style methods extended to dynamic settings).\n\nThus, while both ideas are strong, **Idea 0 (LATE-CT)** offers greater novelty because it introduces a fully differentiable, online-adaptive control mechanism via bilevel optimization—an approach that has not been applied to joint contrastive and pseudo-label training with adaptive temperature—and enables gradient-based learning of the temperature controller itself, which goes beyond what any of the related papers achieve. It avoids reliance on pre-collected meta-data or offline training, making it a more integrated and theoretically grounded advancement in self-training dynamics.\n\nRESPONSE: \n```json\n{\"Decision Made\": \"Idea 0\"}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[96mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "d87e2a49822c422ea06ee4100a1bc686", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 02:01:09", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "THOUGHT:  \nBoth Idea 0 (LATE-CT) and Idea 1 (MetaTemp-CT) propose highly novel approaches to adaptive temperature control in contrastive self-training, leveraging uncertainty, consistency, and feature-space density to modulate pseudo-labeling confidence. However, when evaluating against the provided related work, novelty must be assessed not only in isolation but also in terms of differentiation from existing mechanisms such as ATS (Paper 3), curriculum temperature (Paper 4), meta-learning for instance weighting (Paper 5), and meta-learning via in-context tuning (Paper 2).\n\nIdea 0 proposes an end-to-end bilevel optimization framework where a *learned* temperature policy network is trained jointly with the model using implicit differentiation. This approach tightly integrates temperature adaptation into the training dynamics and extends it to both classification and contrastive losses. While powerful, this bears conceptual similarity to meta-learning with implicit gradients as seen in classical MAML variants or DaMSTF (Paper 5), which also uses meta-learning within self-training and constructs validation signals for learning instance importance. Although LATE-CT applies this to temperature control, the core mechanism—bilevel optimization with online meta-updates—is well-established in meta-learning literature, reducing its *relative* novelty despite technical sophistication.\n\nIn contrast, Idea 1 (MetaTemp-CT) introduces a **pre-trained, generalizable meta-network** that is trained offline on a broad corpus of training trajectories across datasets and conditions to predict \"oracle\" temperatures. This plug-and-play design avoids costly online second-order updates and instead leverages cross-task regularities—a true meta-learning paradigm akin to learning heuristics from experience. Crucially, none of the provided papers describe a system where a meta-model is trained *across diverse semi-supervised training dynamics* to generalize temperature control. Paper 3 (ATS) is post-hoc and static; Paper 4 (CTKD) uses a heuristic schedule; Paper 5 (DaMSTF) focuses on sample weighting in domain adaptation, not temperature modulation across tasks. MetaTemp-CT’s use of class-aware density normalization and gating further enhances robustness in low-data regimes, while its deployment simplicity without fine-tuning offers practical advantages.\n\nMoreover, the idea of distilling cross-dataset insights into a reusable calibration controller represents a shift from per-experiment tuning to systematic, transferable calibration intelligence—an underexplored direction in self-training. This broader generalization capability makes MetaTemp-CT more *distinctively novel* than LATE-CT, which remains confined to online adaptation within a single run.\n\nThus, while both ideas are strong, **Idea 1** achieves greater novelty by decoupling meta-learning from online bilevel optimization and instead proposing a reusable, off-the-shelf adaptive module trained over diverse task distributions—an approach not reflected in any of the provided papers.\n\nRESPONSE: \n```json\n{\"Decision Made\": \"Idea 1\"}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[96mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "2c2ce4fc296e4db0bf0cd830a5038f0e", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 02:01:33", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "THOUGHT: \nBoth Idea 0 and Idea 1 propose innovative approaches to adaptive temperature control in contrastive self-training, targeting the core challenge of balancing confidence and generalization in pseudo-labeling under imbalanced semi-supervised learning. However, when evaluating novelty against existing literature, we must assess overlap with prior work.\n\nPaper 4 (\"Calibrating Language Models with Adaptive Temperature Scaling\") is directly relevant—it introduces Adaptive Temperature Scaling (ATS) for post-hoc calibration of LLMs, where temperature is predicted per token based on features. While this shares the high-level concept of adaptive temperature, it operates in a different domain (language modeling, post-fine-tuning calibration), uses static supervision from an SFT dataset, and lacks integration with contrastive learning or self-training dynamics. Thus, it does not subsume the proposed ideas.\n\nPaper 2 (SAT) proposes instance-adaptive augmentation strength via a meta-learner but focuses on identifying augmentation similarity, not temperature scaling or contrastive learning. It operates in text classification and does not involve temperature-controlled softmaxes or pseudo-label filtering via confidence calibration. Hence, limited overlap.\n\nIdea 0 introduces a meta-learning controller (LSTM-based) that observes epoch-level statistics and outputs temperature values. This resembles external policy learning and requires REINFORCE or implicit differentiation. While novel, such meta-controller architectures have precedent in adaptive training (e.g., SAT in Paper 2, AdaMixer, etc.), making the approach somewhat aligned with existing trends in meta-adaptation.\n\nIdea 1 (SCATM), however, proposes a more integrated and architecturally elegant solution: end-to-end learnable, batch-level, self-conditioned temperature modulation via a gating network trained through implicit differentiation using validation loss. Crucially, it internalizes adaptation without a separate controller, uses a memory buffer for long-term class tracking, and couples this with dual-head decoupled objectives and contrastive learning over high-confidence samples. The use of implicit gradients to train the gating network within the self-training loop—while maintaining differentiability and enabling stable joint optimization—is a significant technical distinction. Furthermore, class-specific or sample-wise temperature generation conditioned on real-time context vectors (entropy, consistency, skew) with interpretability and applicability to extreme imbalance regimes pushes beyond current methods.\n\nNo paper in the provided list performs adaptive temperature control *within* the self-training loop in a fully self-conditioned, end-to-end trainable manner with contrastive learning integration. SCATM’s elimination of external controllers enhances scalability and reduces complexity, representing a cleaner and more deployable innovation.\n\nThus, while both ideas are strong, **Idea 1** demonstrates higher novelty due to its architectural integration, avoidance of external meta-learners, and tighter coupling of adaptive calibration with representation learning—all critical advances not covered by existing literature.\n\nRESPONSE: \n```json\n{\"Decision Made\": \"Idea 1\"}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "2ac165867d3848458f21996389a3e016", "timestamp": "2025-12-11 02:01:57", "name": "Scientist1", "content": "THOUGHT: \nBoth Idea 0 and Idea 1 propose innovative approaches to adaptive temperature control in contrastive self-training, targeting the core challenge of balancing confidence and generalization in pseudo-labeling under imbalanced semi-supervised learning. However, when evaluating novelty against existing literature, we must assess overlap with prior work.\n\nPaper 4 (\"Calibrating Language Models with Adaptive Temperature Scaling\") is the most directly related, as it introduces *Adaptive Temperature Scaling (ATS)*—a method that predicts token-level temperature values based on features for post-hoc calibration of LLMs. While this shares the high-level concept of \"adaptive temperature,\" it operates in a different domain (language modeling, post-fine-tuning calibration), uses non-contrastive objectives, and lacks integration with self-training dynamics or contrastive learning. Thus, it does not subsume either idea.\n\nIdea 0 proposes a meta-learning controller (LSTM-based) that adjusts temperature using epoch-level statistics. This resembles traditional meta-learning setups where an external module optimizes hyperparameters. While effective, such architectures have precedent—e.g., SAT (Paper 2) uses a meta-learner for augmentation strength selection, showing that meta-controllers for adaptive SSL are already explored. The use of REINFORCE or implicit differentiation with a validation set is also standard in meta-optimization literature.\n\nIn contrast, Idea 1 (SCATM) eliminates the external meta-controller entirely by embedding adaptation *within* the model via a lightweight, end-to-end trainable gating network conditioned on batch-level context. This internalization of adaptive temperature modulation—trained via implicit differentiation through a validation objective—is more architecturally elegant and avoids potential instability from decoupled meta-updates. Crucially, SCATM integrates memory buffers for rare class tracking, class-specific temperatures, and dual-head separation of classification and contrastive objectives—all aligned with improving generalization in extreme imbalance.\n\nMoreover, SCATM’s self-conditioned, instance- or class-adaptive mechanism goes beyond both fixed temperatures and externally modulated ones, offering a tighter feedback loop between model confidence, pseudo-label quality, and contrastive learning. Its end-to-end trainability and lack of reliance on separate meta-networks distinguish it clearly from SAT (Paper 2) and ATS (Paper 4). No existing paper combines adaptive temperature scaling with contrastive self-training, memory-augmented stability tracking, and implicit gradient-based control within a single unified framework.\n\nThus, while both ideas are strong, **Idea 1** demonstrates higher novelty due to its integrated, self-conditioned design that advances beyond modular meta-learning paradigms toward truly adaptive, internalized control—a step not taken in current literature.\n\nRESPONSE: \n```json\n{\"Decision Made\": \"Idea 1\"}\n```", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[92mScientist1\u001b[0m"}
